data.content:
Yes — use `Assert.IsInstanceOfType`, which combines the type check and gives a clearer failure message:

```csharp
[TestMethod]
public void Create_ReturnsCorrectHandler()
{
    var factory = new HandlerFactory();
    var result = factory.Create("email");

    Assert.IsInstanceOfType<EmailHandler>(result);
    var handler = (EmailHandler)result;
    Assert.AreEqual("email", handler.Type);
}
```

The direct cast `(EmailHandler)result` throws an `InvalidCastException` on failure, which is unhelpful in test output. `IsInstanceOfType` produces a clear assertion message showing expected vs. actual type.

If you're on **C# 11+ / .NET 7+**, you can also combine it with pattern matching to avoid the redundant cast:

```csharp
Assert.IsInstanceOfType<EmailHandler>(result);
if (result is EmailHandler handler)
{
    Assert.AreEqual("email", handler.Type);
}
```
